Parent material & ecosystem effects on fast and slow cycling soil C

J. Beem-Miller

  • Introduction
  • Hypotheses
  • Methods
  • Results
    • Depth profiles
    • ANOVA
    • Marginal mean trends: 2001-2019
    • Respired CO2

Introduction

Thesis: Parent material and climate interact to control radiocarbon content of bulk soil and heterotrophically respired CO2

  • Parent material key factor affecting radiocarbon content of bulk soil
  • Development and persistence of poorly crystalline minerals associated with depleted 14C content of soil organic matter, i.e. soil C persistence
  • Decomposition rates increase with temperature, suggesting 14C of heterotrophically respired CO2 will be closer to atmospheric 14C in warmer sites than in colder sites
  • Climate and parent material interact on geologic timescales: weathering leads to formation of poorly crystalline minerals but eventually to degradation of these minerals over time, e.g. poorly crystalline mineral content is highest in intermediate stages of soil development
  • How do these interactions affect the balance of C stocks stored in soils?

Hypotheses

  1. Bulk soil d\(\Delta\)14C/dt AN < BS < GR
  2. Resp soil d\(\Delta\)14C-CO2/dt cold < cool < warm
  3. Resp soil d\(\Delta\)14C-CO2/dt AN = BS = GR
  4. Parent material will explain more of the variance in the change over time for bulk soil \(\Delta\)14C than ecosystem, because parent material controls the \(\Delta\)14C of slow cycling soil C that dominates the bulk \(\Delta\)14C signal.
  5. Ecosystem will explain more of the variance in the change over time for respired soil \(\Delta\)14C-CO2 than parent material, because ecosystem controls the \(\Delta\)14C of fast cycling soil C that dominates the respired \(\Delta\)14C-CO2 signal.

Methods

I constructed models for \(\Delta\)14C of bulk soil C and heterotrophically respired CO2 as function of parent material, ecosystem, and year. I considered both the two-way and three-way interactions, using models of the form: lm(d14c ~ PM * ECO * year). Prior to modeling I fit the 2001 and 2009 \(\Delta\)14C data to the 2019 sampling depths using a mass-preserving spline weighted by carbon stocks. In order to simplify the analysis and focus on the change in \(\Delta\)14C over time as a function of parent material and ecosystem, I modeled each depth increment separately. I focused only on the top 30cm (i.e. 0-10cm, 10-20cm, and 20-30cm depth increments) owing to a lack of data from the 2001 sampling for depths below ~30cm.

Results

Depth profiles

Fig. 1. Depth profiles of \(\Delta\)14C of bulk soil and respired CO2

Bulk soil points show the mean of three replicate profiles. We composited the profile replicates prior to incubation, and respired data points show the mean of laboratory duplicates. Error bars show ±1 SD for bulk soils and the min. and max. for respired CO2. Respired CO2 from the cold granite soil was extremely depleted in \(\Delta\)14C and thus is excluded for display purposes.

ANOVA

Bulk soil

Both parent material and ecosystem are significant factors for explaining the variance in bulk soil \(\Delta\)14C at all depths (Table 1, Table 2, Table 3). Ecosystem explains more of the variance at the surface (0-10cm) than does parent material (31.4% and 14.1%, for ecosystem and parent material, respectively) (Table 1). Deeper in the soil, starting at 10-20cm, the relative importance of these two factors switches (Table 2), and by 20-30cm parent material explains 25% of variance in bulk soil \(\Delta\)14C compared to 11.4% for ecosystem (Table 3). The two-way interaction between parent material and ecosystem is signficant in the top 20cm (p < 0.05), but not at the deepest depth.

Year is highly significant at the surface (p < 0.0001, Table 1), but is only marginally significant in the deeper soil layers (p < 0.10) (Table 2, Table 3). Interestingly, the two-way interaction between ecosystem and year is much more significant than the interaction between parent material and year at all depths. This appears to be driven by the strong decrease in cool site \(\Delta\)14C over time relative to the warm or cold sites (Fig. 16b).

Overall, the models explains less of the variance in the data as we go deeper in the soil: 73%, 61%, and 56% for 0-10cm, 10-20cm, and 20-30cm, respectively (Table 1, Table 2, Table 3).

Respired CO2

The relative importance of parent material and ecosystem factors for explaining the variance in \(\Delta\)14C-CO2 depends on depth, as with bulk soil \(\Delta\)14C. Similar to bulk soil, ecosystem explains more of the variance in \(\Delta\)14C-CO2 at the surface (0-10cm) than does parent material. Unlike bulk soil \(\Delta\)14C, however, parent material is not a significant term in the model for \(\Delta\)14C-CO2 at the surface. Parent material becomes a significant factor at the 10-20cm depth, and in fact explains more variance than does ecosystem at this depth, although both effects are significant (p < 0.0005). At the deepest depth (20-30cm), ecosystem is no longer a siginficant predictor of \(\Delta\)14C-CO2 but parent material is strongly siginficant (p = 0.006).

[Year, interactions, overall variance explained] Year, and the two-way interactions are all significant.

All main effects and interactions are significant for \(\Delta\)14C-CO2 at this depth. In contrast to bulk soil \(\Delta\)14C, year is highly significant for \(\Delta\)14C-CO2 (p < 0.0001), while the interaction between parent material and year is also strongly significant (p = 0.001).

Year is highly signficant, as is the two-way interaction of ecosystem and year. Parent material only provides siginificant explanaotry power when considered in a three-way interaction with ecoystem and year.

Marginal mean trends: 2001-2019

The next set of plots show least-square mean estimates of trends within parent material and ecosystem groups for the time period 2001 to 2019. Plots are shown for each depth increment. The first two plots show the full model with interactions between parent material and ecosystem. The same curves are shown twice, but grouped differently to emphasize differences across each level of the grouping factors. Finally, I show the estimated trend and associated confidence intervals for the change in \(\Delta\)14C over time averaged across either parent material or ecosystem. Also shown is the raw data.

Following each plot I show the contrasts for the slope estimates within parent material and ecosystem groups. The first set of numbers show marginal means estimated within groups; second set of numbers show the contrasts, i.e. are the trends over time significantly different between different parent materials or ecosystems?

Bulk soil

0-10cm

Fig. 2. a) parent material

b) ecosystem

In Fig. 5a we can see clearly the strong effect of ecosystem on the temporal trend in bulk soil \(\Delta\)14C. Curves are much steeper at the warm site for all three parent materials, while they are nearly flat at the coldest site. However, at the cool site we can also see the effect of parent material within the climate grouping. The steepest slope and the most enriched \(\Delta\)14C is seen in the granite soils, while the andesite soils show no change in \(\Delta\)14C over time and are also much less enriched. Overall, rates of change in granite and basalt soils were not significantly different in any of the ecosystems. However, the andsite soils are changing significantly faster than the basalt soils at the warmest sites and significantly slower than the granite soils at the cool sites (Table 7).

Considering the contrasts between ecosystems within parent materials (Fig. 5b, Table 8), for the andesite soils we see faster changes over time for the warm site relative to the cool and cold sites (p = 0.0006, and p = 0.0657 respectively). For the granite soils, however, we see faster rates of change at the cool sites than at the warm sites. Unsurprisingly, the rate of change for the cool granite sites is greater than at the cold sites (p = 0.0105).
